p dee boersma the leopold leadership program skip to main content search this site the leopold leadership program about fellows news fellowship information resources fellows login home 2013 fellowship information all cohort reunion june 19 21 2012 in this section fellows directory one of the best things i have ever done in my career it changed my views of how to do my job alan townsend 2001 p dee boersma p dee boersma contact information in my view the two biggest challenges humanity faces are human consumption and human numbers what the world becomes depends on our individual decisions and our collective policies professor and wadsworth endowed chair in conservation science university of washington dr dee boersma's academic research is in the area of conservation biology and has focused on seabirds as indicators of environmental variation including climate change her main interest is in penguins and she has studied several species including one of the rarest and most northerly species of penguins the galapagos penguin and one of the most abundant the magellanic penguin she has been at the university of washington since 1974 when she began her career as an assistant professor of environmental studies and zoology she is a professor of biology and holds the wadsworth endowed chair in conservation science and is the director of the center for penguins as ocean sentinels she was associate director of the institute for environmental studies from 1987 1993 since 1982 dr boersma has also directed the magellanic penguin project at punta tombo argentina in her role as a scientific fellow for the wildlife conservation society since 1982 she has carried out research on magellanic penguins in the south atlantic as they are an important flagship species for conservation and economic development of nature based tourism her research includes assessing their biological characteristics and the effects of human perturbations and policy changes on their survival dr boersma taken on national and international leadership and advisory positions in such diverse roles as member of the board of trustees of central michigan university as an advisor to the united states delegation to the united nations world population conference in romania as a member of president nixon's task force of women's rights and responsibilities and as a member of the board of directors of zero population growth she is a past president of the society for conservation biology and the executive editor of conservation magazine which she helped start tags argentina biodiversity central & south america galapagos ocean sentinels oceans & coasts penguins petroleum pollution public health seabirds storm petrels 2012 leopold leadership program the stanford woods institute for the environment stanford university stanford ca 94305
